{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Gateway max allowances persist after router deauthorization","locations":["onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/contracts/RubicProxy.sol:81","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/libraries/SmartApprove.sol:19","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/libraries/SmartApprove.sol:22","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/BridgeBase.sol:380"],"claim":"`routerCall` grants `_gateway` a `type(uint256).max` allowance on the route token through `SmartApprove`, and that approval is never revoked after execution or when the gateway/router is removed from `availableRouters`. A previously allowlisted gateway contract therefore keeps spender rights over any approved token balance that remains on the proxy.","impact":"If the proxy later holds that token again, for example from accrued protocol fees or stranded user balances, a compromised or malicious current/former gateway can still pull those funds with `transferFrom` even after operators believe it has been deauthorized.","paths":["A user executes `routerCall` through an allowlisted gateway.","`SmartApprove` raises the proxy's allowance for the gateway to `type(uint256).max`.","The transaction completes, but no allowance cleanup occurs.","Later, even after `removeAvailableRouter(_gateway)`, the gateway uses its stale allowance to pull proxy-held balances of that token."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"medium","title":"ERC20 routes spend the declared amount instead of the amount actually received","locations":["onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/contracts/RubicProxy.sol:69","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/contracts/RubicProxy.sol:73","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/contracts/RubicProxy.sol:81","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/contracts/RubicProxy.sol:91","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/BridgeBase.sol:174","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/BridgeBase.sol:190"],"claim":"`routerCall` transfers `_params.srcInputAmount` from the caller but never measures how many tokens the proxy actually received. Fees, approval size, and the post-call spend check are all based on the nominal input amount, so fee-on-transfer or other balance-deflating tokens can cause the proxy to spend more than the user contributed.","impact":"Any pre-existing balance of the same token on the proxy, including accrued protocol fees or previously stranded funds, can be consumed to cover the shortfall. This lets an attacker use a deflationary token deposit to drain proxy reserves of that token.","paths":["The proxy already holds some balance of a token that transfers less than the requested `srcInputAmount`.","An attacker calls `routerCall` with that token and a nominal amount larger than the net amount the proxy will receive.","`accrueTokenFees` and `SmartApprove` still treat the nominal amount as available and allow the downstream spender to use `_amountIn`.","The missing portion is silently funded from the proxy's existing token balance, and the balance-delta check still passes because it only verifies total tokens spent from the proxy."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Users can impersonate any integrator to obtain its custom fee schedule","locations":["onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/contracts/RubicProxy.sol:71","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/contracts/RubicProxy.sol:107","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/BridgeBase.sol:140","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/BridgeBase.sol:217","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/BridgeBase.sol:311","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/BridgeBase.sol:319"],"claim":"The contract trusts the user-supplied `_params.integrator` address when applying both token-fee and fixed-fee discounts. There is no authentication that the caller is actually routing through that integrator, so any user can claim the fee profile of a partner that was configured with cheaper pricing.","impact":"Custom partner pricing becomes a public fee-bypass mechanism. If any integrator is configured with reduced or zero fees, arbitrary users can route under that profile and reduce or eliminate protocol revenue at scale.","paths":["A manager sets discounted fee parameters for a partner with `setIntegratorInfo`.","A user submits a route while setting `_params.integrator` to that partner address.","`routerCall`/`routerCallNative` load that fee profile directly from `integratorToFeeInfo` and apply it without any proof of authorization.","The user receives the cheaper pricing while the protocol and/or intended partner segmentation loses revenue."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"Low","confidence":"medium","title":"Configured per-token min/max limits are never enforced","locations":["onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/contracts/RubicProxy.sol:61","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/contracts/RubicProxy.sol:96","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/BridgeBase.sol:31","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/BridgeBase.sol:33","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/BridgeBase.sol:124","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/BridgeBase.sol:125","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/BridgeBase.sol:343","onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/BridgeBase.sol:356"],"claim":"The protocol stores and exposes administrator-managed `minTokenAmount` and `maxTokenAmount` settings, but neither `routerCall` nor `routerCallNative` ever read or enforce those limits during execution.","impact":"Users can bypass the configured size controls entirely and submit dust-sized or oversized routes. If operators rely on these knobs to prevent uneconomical processing or cap exposure per token, those protections are ineffective and can be griefed permissionlessly.","paths":["Managers configure `minTokenAmount`/`maxTokenAmount` for a token.","A user submits a route whose size is below the minimum or above the maximum.","The execution paths never consult the configured bounds.","The route proceeds despite violating the configured limits."],"round":1,"source_agents":["merge-review"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Request events can advertise arbitrary bridge parameters that are not bound to actual execution","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"The issue is event-only in this codebase. `RequestSent` merely echoes user-supplied parameters after a successful call, and no on-chain logic here relies on that event. The claimed harm depends on unspecified off-chain consumers, so it is too speculative to report as a protocol vulnerability."}]}
